<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
Weeks, months, perhaps even years--as she rested, Carezzia came to understand that, in the realms of the fairy, there is no time.  They never hurried, never betrayed a sense of urgency.  Things happened in an order but not by a schedule.<br /><br />To learn how her family had been lost, to see all the sacrifices made on her behalf, for her security, was a terrible burden but she could accept it.  In many ways, she already had, coming to terms, over the years, with the absence of her parents and her estrangement from her family.  Her grief for Quildluane was fresher, more real and immediate, than for the parents she had never known.<br /><br />But to know that even revenge had been taken from her, that the fairy had contrived, even for the best of motives, to redress all of the ancient grievances, to insulate her from every aspect of the tragedies of her past, left her feeling as if she had been shut out from her own life, deprived in some way of even being herself, like a child so sheltered from the pains of reality that she was never allowed to truly grow up.  It galled her, ate away at her heart--a seed of resentment trying to blossom into something, she did not know what but it was dark and vile--and she began to fear herself as she swung between emotional poles of anger and despair.  And all the time, the fairy moved about her, oblivious to her anguish in their midst.  With all the time in the world to care for matters of honor and vengeance, they seemed blind to the consuming urgency and the fanatical, frustrated need for action in a mortal.<br /><br />Unnoticed by the young druidess, ice grey eyes watched her, knowing, gauging, waiting for the right moment.  Joleena alone understood the process that was taking place and, at last, summoned Carezzia again to the silent pool of mercurial scrying.<br /><br />The elf answered the summons in a fury, prepared to make demands, prepared to argue the injustice of it all, prepared for something, she was not sure, but certainly she would have her say even--if she did not know what it was she wished to say.<br /><br />Instead, before she could speak, the fairy's gaze froze her.  Utterly alien in its cold ruthlessness, Carezzia met the piercing stare that made the girl feel suddenly naked.<br /><br />"You believe that you are the center of the universe?" Joleena spat without provocation.  "That only you were affected by these events?  That yours alone is the claim to revenge?"  She pointed to the pool.  "Learn!"<br /><br />Carezzia let her hand trail across the pastel palette of the water and saw, even muted through the veil of time, a scene of horror...<br /><br /><br /><br />Rows of tables, stone, metal, wood, some new, some old and battered, all caked and stained with blood and ichor.  Feir'dal, whole and in parts, draped, strapped, laid across the surfaces.  Here, fresh blood still dripping from torn flesh.  There, rotting putrescence, long dead and ignored.  Eyes, glazed in death, pressed closed in barely living anguish, staring blankly in shock and madness at nothing.  The only light was that of braziers of coals, casting merciful shadows, flaring to brighter light when bits of flesh were tossed into them.  An abattoir of maniacal proportions...<br /><br />"No!" Carezzia screamed and jerked her hand away, liquid running from her fingers a deep red as if she had dipped them, not in water, but in blood.<br /><br />The fairy clamped her wrist in iron fingers and shoved it back into the pool.  "Look!"<br /><br /><br /><br />Among the bodies, one constant:  all were women.  Some, chained to the tables; on others, limbs had been severed.  In places, mutilated bodies of the dead had been cast disdainfully to the floor that the surface might be used again.  Cowled figures moved in the nightmare, black hands extending to poke and prod ravaged tissues.  Another constant, slow to emerge above the shock of the slaughter:  each Feir'dal had been eviscerated, a bloody cut from sternum to waist.  In some, the cut revealed an inner tumor of flesh, half children, twisted with malformation.  Other, full-formed babes lay dead alongside their carriers.<br /><br />"Did any of the investments survive?"  T'Enel's voice, hoarse, devoid of emotion.  <br /><br />"None."  A young T'Veren.  "This batch was better than the last.  Fewer miscarriages but all those we removed were either stillborn or too monstrous to live long.  You were right.  The fairy infusion seemed to stabilized the maternal systems.  Within a few more batches, varying the injections, we could have had a successful crossbreed."<br /><br />"There will not be any more batches.  That damned Majialenne saw to that.  A pity, to come so close...  Take the bodies down through the Warren tunnels and let the river wash them away.  We're done here.  Oh, and see to it that none of the servitors are left alive to speak of this."<br /><br /><br /><br />Carezzia pulled back with a shuddering breath.  "That was what my parents died to stop?  That was T'Enel's experiment?"<br /><br />Joleena nodded soberly.  "A transgression against even the gods themselves.  Feir'Dal women raped, impregnated by Teir'Dal seed to create crossbreeds with arcane power unseen since the Sundering.  He was distilling fairy blood into injections to keep them alive long enough to bring the spawn to term.  Light elf, dark elf, and fairy blood all in one being.  He wanted to do what only the gods have ever done.  He was creating a new race."<br /><br />Carezzia sat in shocked horror for long moments.  "But he was stopped.  He failed, didn't he?"<br /><br />The fairy noble did not answer and Carezzia reached back into the pool...<br /><br /><br /><br />Bodies half-dammed the bitter cold water of the subterranean river, forgotten in the bitter depths below Neriak, a silent mass of pale, bloating flesh, too cold and too deep for even insects to find.<br /><br />A robed figure struggled to keep balanced on the shifting, macabre terrain, searching for something among the ruin, stabbing downward with an iron staff for purchase on the slippery flesh.<br /><br />The form dropped to its knees and began to dig into the ichors.  In Carezzia's mind, she thought the searcher looked familiar, like Serrapoth, like Descourge, but different.<br /><br />He pulled something from the carnal mound.  A baby.  No, it was lightly furred and bore a tiny tail...a puppy?  The searcher wiped the wetness away from the creature's nose and mouth and delicately put it to his own.  Puffing.  Wiping mucous that ran from its orifices.  Puffing again until, at last, the tiny beast gave a whimper.  The searcher wrapped the cur within the folds of his robes and the waters swirled...<br /><br /><br /><br />"I...what was that?  Who?"  the young druidess stammered.<br /><br />Joleena did not answer directly.  "An aberrant birth, not even bipedal.  Dead but not so far gone that that he could not be reached.  The pup was suckled by a wolf-bitch for almost a year and hunted wild for that long again before the rangers in Surefall captured it.  For lack of understanding, they shifted his form to roughly human and raised him.  Truth be told, he was too wild, too vicious and filled with rage.  They were relieved when he left them to study with the Unkempt.  Given the circumstances of his birth, it was no surprise to me that my son chose to follow Karana.  I don't believe he ever really had a choice."<br /><br />Carezzia's mouth gaped open.  "The pup?  Yes, that was Descourge?"<br /><br />"Of course.  Who else could have been forged into such a tool for our revenge?"<br /><br />***<br /><br />"You are the Keeper of T'Ere's warrens?"<br /><br />The menial did not lift his gaze from the guard's heavy boots.  "I am."<br /><br />"The Seer is available.  You will go directly into her.  You will not vary in your path.  You will do exactly and expressly as she commands and you will do all of this without hesitation.  The Seer serves the Hand of Innoruuk directly and you will respect her accordingly.  Is all of this clear?"<br /><br />"It is."<br /><br />"Very well.  Enter."<br /><br />The Keeper shuffled down the stone hallway and into the room indicated.  Only when he was safely inside did he dare look up.  The room was both small and astoundingly spartan.  A Teir'Dal priestess sat behind a simple wooden table, a deck of cards cradled in one hand.  She motioned wordlessly to the room's only other furnishing, a chair directly across the table from her, identical to the one in which she was setting.  He sat and waited as she shuffled the cards from one hand to another, observing that, even by Teir'Dal standards, she was a surprisingly small woman.<br /><br />"Do you understand why you have been summoned here?" she asked at length.<br /><br />"Not completely, no, m'lady."<br /><br />"Be at ease.  This is a simple thing, little more than a formality.  The Lord T'Veren has requested a reading of the weird all personnel newly acquired within his house.  It is a simple precaution against betrayal.  I shall lay the cards to read your weird and, unless you are more than you say, you may return to your duties.  Simple enough, is it not?"<br /><br />"I simply sit here?"<br /><br />"Exactly so.  Be patient as I concentrate upon you."  She began to lay cards in front of her in a pattern.  "Just a single pass, I think.  There's no reason to read too deeply on a servant."<br /><br />She began to flip the cards over, speaking lightly as she did so.  "Oh, the Magus of Power.  Be flattered, you are wise.  Four wards, good worker.  Ace of Swords reversed, hmmm, usually disaster but could be a reference to T'Enel's tyranny over his help.  And, here central..."<br /><br />The Seer's voice trailed off as she stared at the card face up on the table.  Painted across the placard's face was a wolf facing dexter below a seven-tined antler.  A long spear was superimposed over the top of both, centering the card.  In the deck of a Feir'dal seer, such a symbol would be called The Hunter.  In the deck of the Teir'dal, the card was not used.<br /><br />"Your coming is not wholly unexpected," she eventually said in a strained voice.  "You could easily kill me before I called for help."<br /><br />"Messy," the Keeper replied casually.  "It would make the rest of my work difficult though not impossible."<br /><br />The Seer licked her lips nervously.  "There is no love lost between the Hand and the House T'Enel.  An agreement, perhaps?"<br /><br />"Your life for your silence?  I think not.  It is too cheap, too easy to betray me later."<br /><br />"Then I will ask for more, to make the bargain valuable."<br /><br />The Keeper nodded.  "I can appreciate that."<br /><br />"Duty requires I have your assurance that you are not acting against Neriak, the Hand, or Innoruuk himself."<br /><br />"I can give you that easily.  The cards have already told you as much or you would already have tried to call out.  I assure you, this is, indeed, personal and specific."<br /><br />The priestess bowed her head.  "Then grant me this:  I shall hold your secret.  In exchange, you will look favorably upon my family, now and in the future...including my son.  He is in exile and disgrace but..."<br /><br />"But he is still family.  I accept your offer."  The Keeper stood.  He reached and lifted the Seer's hand to the lips of his metal mask, as if in a kiss.  "It has been a genuine pleasure."<br /><br />***<br />Sweat beaded nervously on T'Veren's upper lip and his breathing was too fast.  Behind a thin mask of calm, his mind raced.  He was a warrior, a risk taker, and he knew fear--only a fool did not--but this, the beast which stalked the periphery of his mind, this was worse.  It was dread.  Fear was a quicksilver clench on the battlefield; this was meaner, the fear of fear, a millstone, slow and sure.<br /><br />He was the foremost of the trio threading their way through the labyrinth depths of the caverns beneath Neriak.  Rene followed him closely and Even'gel brought up the rear, humming happily to herself.<br /><br />She was mad; he was certain of that now, lost completely in whatever dank world of fantasy her mind created for her.  But she was also the wife of his Lord, he could no more defy her orders than grow an additional limb; it simply was not in him.  To do so would run contrary to decades of loyal service and, within the maelstrom which was the House of T'Enel, the immutability of his character was his only anchor of self.  No, T'Veren would not unman himself and flee though every fiber and instinct in his being screamed at him to do so.<br /><br />Even'gel was dangerous in the way only the truly mad could be:  detached and ruthless, utterly without scruple for, in her psychosis, no rules, no visage of commonality remained, only her desires and the implacable will to achieve them.  Over the past month, T'Veren had seen her obsession with T'Ere grow in proportion to her madness.  She clung to her husband with the brutal, desperate savagery of a drowning woman to a swimmer, dragging them both down with her struggles.  It was a sadistic cycle, twisting back upon itself as a snake consuming its own tail.  By clutching, she drove him further from her, driving T'Ere to increasingly hurtful, painful, even physically violent rebuttals.  But these rebukes were attention nonetheless and she fed upon them, turning them in her mind into gestures of affection.  As T'Ere's resentment grew, so too did Even'gel's instability and her pleasure.<br /><br />T'Veren had seen it all play out, horrified yet unable to turn away, hopeless  to avoid the familial tableau as it stretched before him.  He had felt it as well, a swelling tension, a hunting dread, the absolute, grinding pressure leading up to something.  What, he could not guess, but it was there, the feeling, like an animal in the forest, unable to see its hunters yet knowing as sure as sight that the net was closing in around him.<br /><br />She had sent the boy, Rene, to him with her summons--a watchful eye to insure that he complied immediately, that he would not detour to alert T'Enel.  He felt the rope about his neck then and knew he had no choice but to accept it, to ride out the whirlwind and hope to survive, blind but afraid.  When, upon reaching her, she had silently handed him the heavy, corroded iron key he had thought safely locked away deep within T'Enel's most carefully hidden secrets, he had hesitated.  For one, long second the world was still, crystal and sharp, his heart hammered upward into his throat, almost gagging him.  Then he had bowed his head to the yoke and taken the key, leading the way down, into the caverns, into the past.  What purpose she had in taking the boy to the dark machine beneath, he did not even question.<br /><br />He paused again at the lock of the door, another crystal moment of turning, a fork in the road of fate.  T'Veren steadied his hand, turned the key, and entered a chamber inviolate for half a century.<br /><br />The level of the floor was a lie.  A few yards into the chamber the floor fell away below, the ceiling vaulted above, and in the pit and in the arch stood the machine, the lingering key of the blasphemy of House T'Enel.  Despite it all, T'Veren still looked upon it and saw majesty in the metal beast.<br /><br />"The Lady Even'gel would have T'Veren explain the function of this device.  Rene should understand," crooned Even'gel behind him as she entered the chamber.  He kept his face averted to hide his discomfort.<br /><br />"We distilled the fairy," he said softly, almost reverently, the words echoing in the massive chamber, the cathedral of the machine.<br /><br />The entry ledge over-looked the hopper, a low railing of iron along its edge.  They had designed for convenience, placing the most often used part right at the doorway.  They had made it large, as well.  The fairy were so small; it took so many to make even the tiniest amount of serum.  Elsewhere, the ledge launched into catwalks deeper into their creation.  It needed almost no maintenance; T'Enel and T'Veren had designed well, but the occasional bone could clog part of the tubing.  They had never fully solved the bone problem.  Other issues had been more pressing.<br /><br />Several feet down, within the funneling sides of the hopper, the gratings began.  Razor-wires strung from copper frames, criss-crossing in a grid.  Iron had been too heavy and difficult to work, easier to replace the copper when it wore out.  The wires slid within the frames and the frames slid across each other to create a web of slicing metal, sieving the fairy into a stringy pulp.  The upper grating was set above the others, hinged in the center, set to flip when weight dropped upon it.  The fairy could fly, a lid had been necessary.  Out of sight below the hopper, T'Veren knew the rendering vats would still be bubbling.  They had taken advantage of a natural fissure of lava for their heating source.  Parts of the machine reflected its dull red light.<br /><br />"We took from them the very essence which made them who they were and drained it off into a serum," he added, leaning against the iron rail and gesturing broadly.  From the russet pits, long tubes reached into the chamber's zenith.  Great swooping coils of brass raced above the machine, twisting like mating snakes in the embrace of lead pipes bringing cooling water from the rivers of the warrens.  The lines met but never their contents.  The distillate must remain pure; the water lines were for condensation.  In the end, deep within the machine on a suspended platform through a maze of catwalks, T'Veren knew that the brass spirals met together and ended in one, singular nozzle and, below that nozzle, a flask--always a flask.  A hundred fairy might be slaughtered to fill the carafe just once; not a drop could be wasted.  It had been incredibly difficult but they had done it.  Together, the two men had come so very, very close...<br /><br />T'Veren laughed, his own touch of madness emerging.  "We put their souls in a bottle."  It was terribly funny.  "We decanted their spirits.  It's a pun, you see."<br /><br />"A shared spirit," Even'gel said primly and Rene shoved T'Veren, off-balance, over the railing.  The grating closed and the razored loom wove.<br /><br />   


