<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
"The rest is straightforward," Joleena explained.  "Dessy was, of course kept ignorant of his heritage until he was ready to take his rightful place in the Fey Court as Serrapoth's successor, but we watched him closely.  After he left Surefall, he wandered the frozen mountains and the forests, growing increasingly feral.  What little of human customs he knew, he rapidly forgot and even his speech atrophied.  To this day, he is more fluent in Fairy than in the Common Tongue.<br /><br />"When we began to fear that he was slipping too far away from human to be useful, I contrived for him to meet and marry Maeve.  There have been difficulties, but his family has kept him loosely tied to the mundane world."<br /><br />Carezzia held up her hand to interrupt.  "I'm getting a bit lost.  Who do you mean when you say 'we'?"<br /><br />"Primarily Karana and I, although Tunare certainly has had her input, as has Innoruuk."  The fairy waited politely as Carezzia choked and coughed violently.<br /><br />When she recovered from her surprise, the druidess asked, "And Maeve?  Who was she?"<br /><br />"Well, as I have said, she was the Ancient's wife.  She was also my daughter although you must never let him know that.  I believe the Feir'dal called her Mab, the Warrior-Queen.  Maeve was her avatar for that generation."<br /><br />The elf shook her head to clear it.  "What then?"<br /><br />"We arranged for him to fight in the Dark Elf wars and, predictably, he turned out to have an affinity for war.  Then, to our surprise, he became a pacifist of sorts."<br /><br />Carezzia laughed.  "I've read that part in his notes.  They were not fighting the war right, so he decided that if they were not going to fight to win, he would not fight at all."<br /><br />Joleena nodded then quoted with a mock severity:  'How long can you press your face against the enemy until you become a mirror of what he is?  Good and evil fall by the wayside and this so-called war is but an excuse for gratuitous bullying on both sides, with no intent of changing anything.'<br /><br />"It's even funnier when he turns around and says 'If it is worth fighting for, it is worth killing for.  If it is worth killing for, it is worth murdering for.  By this I judge no war is as effective as a single assassin and the greatest show of power is to not fight at all.'" Carezzia added.<br /><br />The fairy smiled.  "He is right, in his way.  And you notice that most of his gentle nature was a cover for a deep-seated rage.  He is certainly no pacifist when it comes to defending his family.  Ah dear Carezzia, that is why he takes revenge for us, not you.  You are family to him, a debt incurred by the fairy before he was even born, but family nonetheless."<br /><br />The Feir'dal smiled.  "I like that.  It's comforting in a strange way."<br /><br />"I'm glad you approve.  Where was I?  Oh yes.  After the war, he returned home to find that Maeve had died.  We almost lost him then.  He became almost a complete hermit.  He had learned to change form by then so he was impossible to find.  Fortunately for us, his love of his daughters was stronger than his grief, and he eventually came back.  Once they were grown, he went back into hiding to write but he always kept an eye and an ear on the world outside."<br /><br />"And the Erudian?  Where does she fit into the picture?"<br /><br />To Carezzia's surprise, Joleena snorted and scowled.  "I do not like her.  My granddaughters think she is the next incarnation of Mab, come back to look after Descourge, but I rather doubt it.  Still, she has been loyal to my Dessy and an adequate partner.  I've no more to say on that matter!"<br /><br />Carezzia quickly changed the subject.  "How does this tie back to Quildluane's death and my capture?"<br /><br />"When you came back to Lesser Fey, you closed the circle.  It gave T'Enel one last chance to either capture you or to show that he had learned from the punishments already inflicted and, thereby, escape a more extreme judgment.  Obviously, he has not learned and chose his own fate."<br /><br />"You said 'punishments already inflicted.'  What was that?"<br /><br />"His plan offended all the gods, not just ours.  Innoruuk let his only son die and struck his wife barren, a horrible fate for the master of a noble house."<br /><br />Carezzia nodded slowly to herself.  "And Quildluane?  How did he die?  Did T'Enel kill him?"<br /><br />The fairy reached to hold the elf's hand.  "No.  The Ancient did.  Your mentor had been captured by the Mayong's troops.  He was too old and injured already.  Dessy couldn't heal him or rescue him so he killed him to spare Quildluane from torture.  If it is any consolation, he also hunted down the Mayong's agents.  None of them returned home.  I'm sorry, dear.  I know it's a harsh thing, but he thought it best."<br /><br />Carezzia shook her head and cleared her throat.  "No.  It's all right.  I understand."  She smiled without humor.  "I'm a druid.  Death and suffering seems to be an integral part of our calling.  And now?  What becomes of us now?"<br /><br />Joleena grinned and squeezed her hand.  "Now?  Dear child, now we proceed with our lives.  For us, this war is over.  It's time to let it go."<br /><br />***<br /><br />"Keeper!"  Kathrin's voice was harsh, scratching its way out of her throat.  "Keeper!" she shouted again then collapsed forward, wrapping her arms protectively around the searing pain in her chest.  Her mouth was so dry that her tongue was numb.  Her entire body ached just from the exertion of pushing herself upright and her eyes burned, the edges of her vision wavering with tears.<br /><br />The hands that steadied her were gentle but the merest touch forced her to bite back screams of agony.  A clay cup was pressed to her lips and she tried to drink, half the water flowing down her chin instead.  "I'm sorry," the Keeper whisper to her.  "I've done all I can."<br /><br />"How much longer?"  she gasped.<br /><br />"Days, I'm sure, no more.  Don't die, not yet."<br /><br />"One last stab at T'Enel."  She tried to smile at that but could not summon the effort.  "My children, you'll care for them?"<br /><br />In her fevered state, clinging to a life already stretched beyond its limits, she had asked this question repeatedly.  The Keeper answered her as he always did.  "As my own--blood of my blood, bone of my bone."  The words seemed to soothe her and she slipped into a restless sleep.<br /><br />***<br />[Warning:  The following section contains instances of extreme domestic brutality.  Though not rendered at a gratuitous level, these scenes may be disturbing.  Reader discretion is advised.] <br /><br />"Damn it all," growled T'Enel, "Where are the servants?"  He hefted a fluted glass from the table and threw it across the room, enjoying the action and the satisfying crash when it hit the wall.<br /><br />Even'gel was coddling her dog and looked up.  "The Lady Even'gel has sent the servants away that she might enjoy a quiet dinner with her husband."<br /><br />T'Enel clenched his teeth to keep from shouting.  Her insipid use of the third person was like a rasp drawn across his already taut nerves.  A headache was perched behind his eyes like a fat imp beating his brain with a hammer.  At least dinner alone with Even'gel reduced the number of irritations in his life down to one; he would not have to deal with that simpering fool Rene.<br /><br />"Where is T'Veren?  He's been gone for two days now," he complained aloud.  "He knows I can't manage two houses without help, curse him.  If he wasn't my cousin, I'd have him killed just for abandoning me!"<br /><br />Even'gel fluttered a hand at his seat and began to light candles, one from another.  "Do not trouble yourself over these small things, husband.  Sit and eat.  Rediscover your lost love."<br /><br />He rubbed his temples and sat, ignoring her words.  If he could simply tolerate her through this meal, then he could return to work, maybe even get some decent sleep tonight.  He would have to spend the night in his office; otherwise Even'gel would suck the life from what little rest he did get.  He looked across the table to her sallow face and glassy eyes and wondered again why he had married her.  Surely even the power and money the marriage had gained him was not worth this millstone around his neck.<br /><br />"It is suitable?" she asked, seeing his gaze, and T'Enel nodded, eating mechanically.  He washed down the food with a wine almost as tasteless and even saltier.  Even'gel was talking, prattling on about some trivial part of her day; he did not listen, his mind racing forward to dwell on the work that awaited him in his office.  Perhaps the Rileaus brat could help after all; at the least he could run errands while T'Enel worked.  He swallowed another mouthful of the wine.<br /><br />"Where's Rene?" he asked aloud.<br /><br />"The Lady Even'gel has sent him away that she might be alone with her husband.  She has sent him to deal with the great distraction which has consumed her beloved these many years."<br /><br />He squeezed his eyes tight against the pain in his head.  "What are you babbling on about, woman?"<br /><br />"Does the Lady Even'gel's husband not find the wine uniting?"<br /><br />"Even'gel!"  He slammed his fist into the table.  "Enough of your prattling!  What are you talking about?  I'm in no mood to play this game of yours.  What is going on?"<br /><br />"The wine."  Her eyes pooled and her lower lip trembled.  "Do you not like the wine?"<br /><br />T'Enel sank back into his chair.  "The wine is fine," he lied and, to prove his point, gulped the last of it with a grimace.  "What is the big deal about it?"<br /><br />For a moment, he saw her, a flash of the Even'gel he had married, indeed loved, a frightened child peaking out from behind her glassy eyes.  "I miss you, T'Enel.  I wanted us, together.  I did it for us.  We needed a shared spirit."<br /><br />Something in her tone lifted the hair on his neck like a cold wind and he stood, speaking gently.  "Even', what did you do?"<br /><br />The mask was back in place now and she retreated, pressing herself back in her chair.  "The wine.  High Lord T'Enel has loved T'Veren his entire life.  Now same T'Veren has served his house most nobly, binding husband and wife with his shared spirit.  Why, by the very creation of his own hands."<br /><br />His head was pounding; his stomach knotted around a fist of stress and an ill-settled meal; Even'gel's sentences were almost impossible to follow then, in a terrible moment, it all locked into place and T'Enel gripped the edges of the table to keep from falling.  "You fed T'Veren to the machine?" he asked softly, incredulously, then again.  "You fed T'Veren to the machine.  And the wine&amp;#8230;"<br /><br />T'Enel flung the table aside in a crash of glass and silverware.  "You killed T'Veren!  And served him to me like food!"  He advanced on her menacingly, hand lifted to strike at her.<br /><br />He had forgotten the dog--the accursed, overfed, pampered dog.  It growled and snapped at him.  T'Enel kicked at it, the toe of his boot catching it just under the front shoulder.  It yelped and lunged at him, fat and clumsy, tearing the cloth of his breeches.  Furious, T'Enel dropped on it with both knees, a hand on its neck.  The other hand searched behind him, finding a knife, stabbing the struggling mutt in the throat until it stopped struggling.  He stood and threw the knife to one side and kicked the dog's body contemptuously.  <br /><br />Even'gel flew at him, the ineffectual protests of a woman, crying and beating lightly on his chest.  He slapped her then, to shut her up, to push her back.  She startled and pulled away, fixing him with a venomous look.<br /><br />It all rushed up then--the frustration, the anger, the barely realized horror--in the face of that hated look.  As though she had any right!  He hit her, hard.  No slap this time, a solid right jab into that loathsome face.  It felt good.   Something within him tore, and something felt released.  As she raised her hands, he hit her again.  The rage was better than the headache.  He hit her again, knocking her to the floor.  And again when she tried to rise.  Again and again until she did not struggle anymore, until she stopped crying, until she stopped moving, until the moist pulp beneath his fist ceased to crunch with bones, until all resistance was gone.  And then he remembered:  "She has sent him to deal with the great distraction which has consumed her beloved these many years."<br /><br />"Kathrin," he spat and began to run, down through the halls of the House T'Enel toward the warrens.  A guard saw him, covered in splattered blood, wild-eyed and running, and moved toward him.  T'Enel shoved him aside with a snarl, then turned and jerked the sword from the guard's hands, leaving him standing behind, transfixed by his confusion as T'Enel continued to run.<br /><br />When he burst into the central chamber of the warrens, T'Enel saw Rene, standing over an unconscious Kathrin, hesitant, not quite ready to kill in cold blood.<br /><br />"Get away!" he roared at the boy and Rene turned his head, blade pointed at the prostrate elf.<br /><br />He saw then that the Feir'dal had not been unconscious after all.  As Rene turned, she forced herself upward with her knees and elbows, a look of pure hatred fastened on her face and, staring at T'Enel, a sneer crept to her lips.  Before he could move, she threw herself forward, onto Rene's blade.<br /><br />The boy never had a chance to react.  Even as he turned in surprise to see Kathrin's corpse sliding from his sword, T'Enel struck him.  The blow was an overhand, more suited to ax than sword.  It cut through his shoulder, shattering the clavicle, then twisting when it hit the upper ribcage, tearing across Rene's chest and through his left lung, wedging in the broken sternum.  Rene collapsed, gurgling in the froth of his own blood.<br /><br />T'Enel ignored him, releasing the trapped weapon, and fell to the ground, cradling Kathrin's body in his arms.  He did not look up until the Keeper was standing almost atop him.  The menial's bandaged hand now sported two long rods ending in flesh-hooks protruding from the back of a leathered gauntlet.  Casually, as though mindless of the surroundings, the Keeper reached with his free hand to remove his metal mask and cast it aside.<br /><br />"Serrapoth?" T'Enel asked incredulously.  The resemblance was uncanny.<br /><br />"No," the Keeper replied.<br /><br />"Then who--what--"<br /><br />The Keeper laughed sharply.  "You want an explanation?  Gods know that&amp;#8217;s more than I ever got."  The Keeper knelt in front of him and pressed the tips of the flesh-hooks into the soft skin beneath T'Enel's eyes.  "Not Serrapoth,  something more primitive and yet, more modern.  Do you not recognize your own creation?"  The Keeper pressed the hooks harder, into the flesh, and pulled down slowly, forcing T'Enel's eyes to gap open.  "All of this, you did.  All the death, all the sorrow, everything here is yours.  Oh, they planned it but, for a certainty, you earned it."<br /><br />T'Enel raised a hand and etched a sigil into the air.  "By Innoruuk, I&amp;#8230;"  His spell was cut short as a searing pain lanced his arm.  He looked to see the hand and arm wither to a brittle stub.<br /><br />"Never take an oath lightly," the Keeper said dispassionately.  "You swore the Oaths of the Dead, after all.  That was the tricky part, you know.  To remove even the protections of your own god from you."  The Keeper pulled on the hooks, forcing T'Enel's gaze back to his own and winked at him with a nictitating membrane.  "Everything else was planned by the gods but this moment, this one right here, between you and me, they left to me.  My payment, I suppose; my chance to take revenge as I saw fit.  Probably expected me to kill you."<br /><br />T'Enel waited, drained of energy, tired of caring and awash in confusion.<br /><br />"No,"  the Keeper continued.  "I think that I shall give you the one thing which you gave to me, that would be better than revenge, don't you think, to give you justice?  No family, no house, no hope--just life."  The flesh-hooks wrenched down and away, tearing the flesh of T'Enel's eyelids and cheeks, flooding his eyes with hot blood.<br /><br />As he fell, blind in blood, awash with pain, T'Enel felt the body of Kathrin  taken from him and then the rest was silence as he was left, waiting.<br /><br />***<br /><br />On the rocky slopes of the mountains that rise at the northern edge of the western plains of Karana, a small grove of conifers wrings out a solitary existence.  Within the sheltered copse, the wind is a constant sigh and a permanent blanket of brown needles covers the earth beneath.  It is a graveyard of sorts, a type of family plot.  There are no headstones, no monuments, only low cairns of rock laid to preserve the memory of those buried beneath from scavengers.  The number of graves is low, barely distinguishable from the other rocky outcroppings in the area--a wife, a granddaughter, a few sons--and now, one other.<br /><br />The Ancient dug the graves by hand, neither tools nor talents, only the power of his hands, driving into the packed soil, tearing free the clods and stones, prying with broken fingernails.  Physically, he was a poor match for the land and it took its toll upon him.  Skin broke and bled, nails shattered or tore painfully away from his hands, bones would crack and still he would dig, staining the new-cut grave with his own blood, tears, and sweat.  It was a flagellatistic act, a personal atonement for the dead, an external suffering in accord with the internal grief.  It was, by symbol and sorrow, a sacrament as holy as any formalized process and more personal.  Stripped bare of pretense, it was the losing struggle of one man's will against the unforgiving stoicism of nature, and utterly pointless.  Yet whether the act was one of thurification and unction by suffering or a futile gesture of selfish pride, no power above or below would gainsay his right to this most personal of rites--the burial of one's own dead.<br /><br />Satisfied with the depth, he laid the body within, moving slowly, for that was the only speed clenched muscles and exhaustion would allow.  The placement was gentle, as though tucking a child in to sleep.  As he replaced the dirt into the grave, he laid each handful with care, tender as though the deceased were only resting and not to be disturbed, covering the face last and smoothing the soil with the bleeding palms of his hands.  He paused to bite away a torn and hanging strip of flesh from a gash on his forearm, then turned to the stones.<br /><br />Each rock was examined, turned full about and every angle scrutinized by eye and rubbed by hand before its placement.  The cairn was perfect, each stone fitting together like pieces of a giant puzzle, solid and secure, permanent with neither mud nor mortar, streaked russet from bloodied fingers.<br /><br />Done at last, Descourge stood and did nothing--standing and looking down for unmeasured time--no words were spoken, no eulogy given, nothing to indicate "Here lies Kathrin Majialenne, family."  It was enough to know what was.<br /><br />As he had worked, day had passed into night and now crept back to day again.  He turned and walk down from the mountains, unhurried, caught in a moment of ritual outside of time.  He walked for miles, out of the foothills, across the plains and farmlands, to the banks of the slow, muddy river.  Into the river he walked until its waters rose to tease at his beard.  Only then did he stop.<br /><br />He sank, fully beneath the water, robes and hair floating out in a strange dark halo, the marks of his labors flowing away, into the bosom of the river, the blood, the salty mud, the grief of the body.  The grief of mind was his own to keep.<br /><br />Six more times he dipped himself within the river before he was clean.  He strode back to the shore and shook himself like a large, wet dog and twisted his robes to squeeze the weight of the water from them.<br /><br />Some distance away, jutting up from the brush and weeds of years of unchecked growth, rose a fire-blackened chimney.  Near the chimney, flat paving stones formed what might once have been a walking path, perhaps the sill of a doorway.  It was to here, to these ruins retaken by the land, he walked now, meet by the hefty bear cub running in a rolling gait.<br /><br />The Ancient smiled thinly as the bear pushed against his legs with its head.  "All right, Marlowe.  Let's go home."<br />  


