<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
It was two years before Carezzia saw the patriarch of her family again; he had gone to ground and even her newly acquired family would not break his silence.  When Joleena had relented and agreed to send for him, Carezzia's courage had flagged and she had considered not seek him after all.  She was to be married, to a Teir'dal--an exile who had renounced his people but, given her surrogate father's past, she was afraid of his reaction.<br /><br />She need not have worried.  He had come, dressed all in black leather, sternly distinguished.  Meeting the young dark elf who was her suitor, Descourge had laughed suddenly, shook his head in bemusement, and given his blessing.  <br /><br />To her utter delight, the Ancient had given her away, answering the ecclesiastic's "Who gives this woman" with a stern "Her mother and I do."  As he said it, Carezzia had felt her mother's spirit as solidly as she felt the ground beneath her feet.  Upon this moment of pure joy, another glimpse of the layered mystery that was his life was added.  "And who shall speak for the character of this man?" had been answered in the same stern voice with an answer a riddle:  "In accord with assurances given to the Oracles of Neriak, I vouchsafe for him.  He finds favor in my eyes."  No explanation had been offered; she had intended to ask him about it during the reception but, of course, the aging druid had already gone, vanished back into his self-imposed exile.  He had left her a gift in the keeping of her eldest sibling:  a small, clay cup, no inscription, no explanation, another enigma.  But she was happy.  It was enough.<br /><br />***<br /><br />Dearest Sister Carezzia,<br /><br />I trust this finds you well and that your honeymoon was a joyous one.  We have not heard from Father.  I'm sure Grandmother knows where he is but, well, you already know that she is as tight-lipped as he is.  I think they both love secrets as much as they love their children.  The Kerrans speak of a hermit in Stonebrunt who gives candy to the children in trade for catnip and protects the villagers from poachers.  I have my suspicions.<br /><br />During your reception, you asked me a question and, in the hubbub, I didn't get a chance to answer.  It's just as well, explaining why we call Father "Ancient of Days" is tricky.<br /><br />When we were little, before Mama died, they used to sing us to sleep.  It was an old lullaby in fairy.  We didn't understand most of the words, of course.  I got all the words and the translation from Grandmother a few years ago.  The lullaby was a duet.  Father would sing the first half of the line and Mama sang the ending, like a conversation.  After Mama died, it was like he forgot her part of the song.  He was just kind of stuck in his half of the song, like it was all that he had left to describe himself without her.  I don't know a better way to put it.  It was sad.  He's still sad, I think.  <br /><br />Anyhow, I didn't write you to upset you.  I checked with Grandmother, just to make sure, and I wrote the words out for you.  It's translated so the rhythm is all messed up but here it is.  We miss you and I hope you come visit soon.<br /><br />With Love, Your Sister<br />A.<br /><br /><br />To sift through bitter ashes...and find the singed relic<br />To speak in lifeless tongues...that they may never fade<br />To reflect on past injustice...to learn mercy and seek grace<br />To endure the pressing darkness...looking toward the coming dawn<br />To live when hope is gone...for life is more than dreams<br />To dig the graves of children...and know the fields will flower again<br /><br />Standing in the breech...a time to stand alone<br />Weakened from the fray...a time to stand with others<br />Broken from the wars...a time to stand with family<br /><br />This is the duty...which I have chosen<br />This is the cost...which I will pay<br />For I am become...Ancient of Days<br /><br /><br />[Our little play is done.  Performers exit stage right and Curtain.]<br />   


